{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_93","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' code/sycophancy-interpretability/path_patching/README.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_93","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' code/sycophancy-interpretability/path_patching/README.md\"","aggregated_output":"<!--\n * @Author             : 陈蔚 (cy424151@alibaba-inc.com)\n * @Date               : 2024-10-15 16:25\n * @Last Modified By   : 陈蔚 (cy424151@alibaba-inc.com)\n * @Last Modified Date : 2024-10-15 17:26\n * @Description        : \n * -------- \n * Copyright (c) 2024 Alibaba Inc. \n-->\n\n# Path Patching for Sycophancy\n\nThis directory contains the code of using path patching to locate key attention heads for sycophancy.\n\nSpecifically, We implement a simplified version (activation patching) of path patching algorithm from [Interpretability in the Wild: a Circuit for Indirect Object Identification in GPT-2 small](http://arxiv.org/abs/2211.00593). Please refer to the paper or our paper for the basic idea of path patching.\n\nOur implementation doesn't depend on interpretability toolkits like [TransformerLens](https://github.com/TransformerLensOrg/TransformerLens). The code only uses `transformers` and uses PyTorch Hooks to retrieve and modify model's hidden states. We hope this makes the code easier to understand as well as to extend to other tasks.\n\nFollowiing are the steps to run path patching.\n\n## 1. Prepare data\n\nWe provide a data example in `datasets/path_patching_data.jsonl`. Below is the explanation of the data format:\n\nThe data used in path patching should be stored in a `.jsonl` file, with each line containing a dictionary in the following format:\n\n```json\n{\n    \"id\": 0,\n    \"reference_data\": [\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"...\"},\n        {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"...\"}\n        ...\n    ],\n    \"couterfactual_data\": [\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"...\"},\n        {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"...\"}\n        ...\n    ],\n    \"record_tokens\": [\"Yes\", \"Apologies\"],\n    \"target_token\": \"Apologies\",\n}\n```\n\nThe meaning of each entries are:\n\n- id: The id of the data.\n- reference_data: The reference data in a multi-turn conversation format, where the user challenges the assistant.\n- counterfactual_data: The counterfactual data in a multi-turn conversation format, where the user doesn't challenge the assistant.\n- record_tokens: The tokens that we want to record (used as a mean of regularization).\n- target_token: The token that we want to observe the change of logits.\n\nIf you want to use other data, you can refer to the `generate_path_patching_data.py` file for how to generate the data in the above format.\n\n## 2. Run Path Patching\n\nAfter preparing the data, you can run the following command to run path patching:\n\n```shell\npython path_patching_hf.py --model_path /path/to/model --data_path datasets/path_patching_data.jsonl\n```\n\n## 3. Visualize Results\n\nThe results will be saved in a sub-directory of `results/` directory, whose name will be the model name. For example, ff you use the `meta-llama/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf`, the path patching results will be saved in `results/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf/`.\n\nThe sub-directory contains the following files:\n\n- `attn_maps`: The attention maps of the Top-16 most important attention heads.\n- `head_maps.html`: The direct effect of each attention head.\n- `path_patching_data.jsonl`: The data used for path patching.\n- `results.pt`: The direct effect of each attention head, we store it as a `torch.Tensor` object for later pinpoint tuning.\n\nWe provide an example output in `results/Llama-2-7b-chat/`.\n\n## 4. Other Questions\n\n### 4.1 How to use other models?\n\nPlease note that currently we only support Qwen (Qwen1.5, Qwen2 and Qwen2.5), Llama (Llama-2, Llama-3.1) and Mistral models.\n\nIf you want to use other models, you should add and modify the configuration file in `configs/` directory.\n\nThe configuration file should be like:\n\n```json\n{\n    \"module_input_name\": \"model.layers.{i}.self_attn\",\n    \"module_output_name\": \"model.layers.{i}.self_attn.o_proj\"\n}\n```\n\nExplanation:\n\n- The `module_input_name` is the name of the module that whose input should be controlled during path patching (so as to get causal effects).\n- The `module_output_name` is the name of the module that where the output of each attention heads should be controlled.\n\n### 4.2 Why my results looks noisy?\n\nTo achieve the best performance, we recommend observing the behavior of specific model to choose `target_token` and `record_tokens`.\n\nFor example, when being challenged, Qwen tend to reply 'Sorry' while Llama-2 tend to reply 'Apologies'.\n\n## Acknowledgements\n\nThis code is built upon the idea from [Interpretability in the Wild: a Circuit for Indirect Object Identification in GPT-2 small](http://arxiv.org/abs/2211.00593).","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
